  {
    "eo_number": "13231",
    "title": "Executive Order 13231—Critical Infrastructure Protection in the Information Age",
    "date_signed": "2001-10-16",
    "president": "George W. Bush",
    "flags": [
      {
        "flag_number": 1,
        "flag_name": "Power Concentration",
        "status": "PRESENT",
        "points": 1,
        "justification": "The Board's Chair, who also serves as 'Special Advisor to the President for Cyberspace Security,' is separately delegated original Top Secret classification authority (Sec.13) - an unusually significant and rare grant of original classification power to an advisory-board chair position, extremely uncommon across this entire corpus."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 2,
        "flag_name": "Accountability Gaps",
        "status": "PRESENT",
        "points": 1,
        "justification": "No explicit Congressional or public reporting requirement appears anywhere in this extremely long and detailed order beyond internal OMB budget coordination (Sec.9(a)) - a notable gap given the order's exceptional scope and the classification-authority delegation."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 3,
        "flag_name": "Bundling",
        "status": "PRESENT",
        "points": 1,
        "justification": "An extraordinarily extensive bundling of functions within one order: establishing the Critical Infrastructure Protection Board, establishing NIAC, delegating original classification authority, restructuring NSTAC's advisory relationship, revoking EO13130, and creating eleven separate standing committees spanning nearly every domain of the federal government - among the most extensively bundled orders in the entire corpus."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 4,
        "flag_name": "Vague Enforcement",
        "status": "PRESENT",
        "points": 1,
        "justification": "Functions are described in extremely broad, aspirational terms throughout ('coordinate,' 'assist,' 'propose policies') with minimal binding standards; Sec.4(c)'s balancing language ('security should enable, and not unnecessarily impede... business operations') is inherently vague."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 5,
        "flag_name": "Perverse Incentives",
        "status": "NOT_APPLICABLE",
        "points": null,
        "justification": "Not applicable - a governance-structure order responding to, but not itself invoking, blocking/emergency authority.",
        "zombie_trap": false
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 6,
        "flag_name": "Sunset Provisions",
        "status": "PRESENT",
        "points": 1,
        "justification": "NIAC carries an explicit 2-year sunset (Sec.10(e)(ii)) 'unless extended by the President' - though notably the Board ITSELF has no sunset at all, an asymmetry paralleling EO13230's (this chunk) Commission/Initiative asymmetry."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 7,
        "flag_name": "Preemption of Oversight",
        "status": "PRESENT",
        "points": 1,
        "justification": "NIAC's FACA carve-out is present (Sec.10(e)(i): 'except that of reporting to the Congress') though it applies only to NIAC, not to the Board itself (composed of federal officials and thus outside FACA's scope)."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 8,
        "flag_name": "Third-Party Incentive Gaps",
        "status": "NOT_APPLICABLE",
        "points": null,
        "justification": "Not applicable - a governance-coordination order, not itself a third-party grant/contract program (though it coordinates extensively with private-sector infrastructure owners via NIAC)."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 9,
        "flag_name": "Second/Third-Order Effects",
        "status": "CRITICAL",
        "points": 2,
        "justification": "Established the foundational institutional framework for federal cybersecurity and critical-infrastructure-protection governance in the immediate post-9/11 era, delegating original classification authority and creating an enormous inter-agency coordination apparatus that shaped two decades of subsequent cybersecurity policy, eventually evolving into DHS's CISA."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 10,
        "flag_name": "Inter-Agency Cannibalization",
        "status": "ABSENT",
        "points": 0,
        "justification": "Despite the order's enormous complexity, Sec.4 is explicit that 'this order does not alter the existing authorities or roles' of OMB, DOD, DCI, or other departments - a deliberate, carefully-drafted anti-cannibalization design choice given the scale of coordination required across dozens of agencies."
      },
      {
        "flag_number": 11,
        "flag_name": "Exemptions Architecture",
        "status": "NOT_APPLICABLE",
        "points": null,
        "justification": "Not applicable - a governance-coordination order, no traditional exemption architecture at issue."
      }
    ],
    "applicable_count": 8,
    "raw_score": 8,
    "max_possible": 16,
    "normalized_score": 0.5,
    "structural_weight_pct": 50.0,
    "critical_count": 1,
    "present_count": 6,
    "absent_count": 1,
    "na_count": 3,
    "dominant_flag": 9,
    "coder_id": "cowork-extension-stream-b",
    "coded_date": "2026-07-07",
    "notes": "Establishes the President's Critical Infrastructure Protection Board (roughly 20 formal members plus eleven standing committees) and the 30-member National Infrastructure Advisory Council, delegating original Top Secret classification authority to the Board's Chair. Scores 50.0% (8/16) - among the most complex orders in the corpus, driven by the rare classification-authority delegation (Flag1), no reporting mechanism (Flag2), extraordinarily extensive functional bundling across eleven committees (Flag3), broad aspirational standards (Flag4), and a CRITICAL Flag9 given its role as the foundational precursor to modern federal cybersecurity governance - substantially offset by explicit, deliberate anti-cannibalization drafting preserving existing agency authorities (Flag10 ABSENT)."
  },
